   <td>69.7</td>\n      <td>0.036</td>\n      <td>0.0</td>\n      <td>85.7</td>\n      <td>46.05</td>\n      <td>1</td>\n      <td>0</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>3</th>\n      <td>2025-01-01 00:14:27</td>\n      <td>2025-01-01 00:20:01</td>\n      <td>3.0</td>\n      <td>0.52</td>\n      <td>1.0</td>\n      <td>244</td>\n      <td>244</td>\n      <td>2</td>\n      <td>9.70</td>\n      <td>0</td>\n      <td>...</td>\n      <td>Manhattan</td>\n      <td>Washington Heights South</td>\n      <td>0</td>\n      <td>69.7</td>\n      <td>0.036</td>\n      <td>0.0</td>\n      <td>85.7</td>\n      <td>46.05</td>\n      <td>1</td>\n      <td>0</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>4</th>\n      <td>2025-01-01 00:21:34</td>\n      <td>2025-01-01 00:25:06</td>\n      <td>3.0</td>\n      <td>0.66</td>\n      <td>1.0</td>\n      <td>244</td>\n      <td>116</td>\n      <td>2</td>\n      <td>8.30</td>\n      <td>0</td>\n      <td>...</td>\n      <td>Manhattan</td>\n      <td>Hamilton Heights</td>\n      <td>0</td>\n      <td>69.7</td>\n      <td>0.036</td>\n      <td>0.0</td>\n      <td>85.7</td>\n      <td>46.05</td>\n      <td>1</td>\n      <td>0</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n<p>5 rows × 34 columns</p>\n</div>"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":4},{"id":"6f5df802-3772-4e4c-bb24-e6ba52008e17","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 5. Train / Test Split\n\nThe train/test split is performed **at this point**, before any aggregation or statistical summarization of the target variable. This ordering is deliberate: any feature that is computed using fare information must be derived from training data only, or it constitutes data leakage.\n\nWe use an 80/20 split with a fixed random state.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"b04dd731-3cbb-4f3d-917a-171f816085e1","cell_type":"code","source":"# Drop raw datetime columns no longer needed\ndf = df.drop(columns=['tpep_pickup_datetime', 'tpep_dropoff_datetime', 'PU_Zone', 'DO_Zone'], errors='ignore')\n\nTARGET = 'total_amount'\nX = df.drop(columns=[TARGET])\ny = df[TARGET]\n\nX_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\n    X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=RANDOM_STATE\n)\nprint(f\"Train: {X_train.shape}  |  Test: {X_test.shape}\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:09:15.445719Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:09:15.445946Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:09:17.504568Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:09:15.445922Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:09:17.503805Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Train: (2612378, 29)  |  Test: (653095, 29)\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":5},{"id":"a965ae67-afb7-458d-bd08-93e24ebbbfca","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 6. Leakage-Free Demand Features\n\nZone-level demand patterns are strong predictors of fare — some pickup zones consistently yield higher fares, and certain hours are busier than others. We capture this with three aggregated statistics per `(PULocationID, hour)` pair:\n\n- `zone_hour_avg_fare` — mean fare for that zone at that hour (a learned prior)\n- `zone_hour_ride_count` — number of rides (proxy for demand level)\n- `zone_hour_fare_std` — standard deviation of fares (measures pricing uncertainty)\n\n**Critically**, these statistics are computed **on the training set only** and then joined onto both train and test splits. Computing them on the full dataset before the split would leak test-set information into training — a common and hard-to-spot mistake. Zones unseen in training are filled with the global training mean.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"cdc335a2-3ec1-46bf-b543-a8c0ab0c2a1b","cell_type":"code","source":"def compute_demand_features(train_df: pd.DataFrame, target: pd.Series) -> pd.DataFrame:\n    \"\"\"Compute zone/hour demand stats from training data only.\"\"\"\n    tmp = train_df[['PULocationID', 'hour']].copy()\n    tmp['total_amount'] = target.values\n\n    zone_hour = tmp.groupby(['PULocationID', 'hour']).agg(\n        zone_hour_avg_fare   = ('total_amount', 'mean'),\n        zone_hour_ride_count = ('total_amount', 'count'),\n        zone_hour_fare_std   = ('total_amount', 'std')\n    ).reset_index()\n    zone_hour['zone_hour_fare_std'] = zone_hour['zone_hour_fare_std'].fillna(0)\n    return zone_hour\n\n\ndemand_stats = compute_demand_features(X_train, y_train)\n\nX_train = X_train.merge(demand_stats, on=['PULocationID', 'hour'], how='left')\nX_test  = X_test.merge(demand_stats,  on=['PULocationID', 'hour'], how='left')\n\n# Fill zones unseen in training\nfor col in ['zone_hour_avg_fare', 'zone_hour_ride_count', 'zone_hour_fare_std']:\n    global_mean = X_train[col].mean()\n    X_train[col] = X_train[col].fillna(global_mean)\n    X_test[col]  = X_test[col].fillna(global_mean)\n\nprint(\"Demand features added. New shape:\", X_train.shape)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:09:17.505188Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:09:17.505385Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:09:19.608452Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:09:17.505366Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:09:19.607852Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Demand features added. New shape: (2612378, 32)\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":6},{"id":"570f172c-3cba-461d-986b-c3a9aa054618","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 7. Preprocessing Pipeline\n\nWe separate features into categorical and numerical groups.\n\nCategorical columns (`PULocationID`, `DOLocationID`, `PU_Borough`, `DO_Borough`, `RatecodeID`, `payment_type`) are encoded using `OrdinalEncoder`. For tree-based models like XGBoost, ordinal encoding is preferred over one-hot encoding: it avoids creating a high-dimensional sparse matrix while still allowing the model to split on category values effectively. Unknown categories encountered at inference time are assigned the value `-1`.\n\nAll other numeric columns pass through unchanged via `remainder='passthrough'`. The fitted preprocessor is applied once here and reused for both the regressor and classifier.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"71ef3338-2aca-436f-a1d7-971c5d26c313","cell_type":"code","source":"from sklearn.preprocessing import OrdinalEncoder\n\n# Identify column types\ncat_cols = ['PULocationID', 'DOLocationID', 'PU_Borough', 'DO_Borough', 'RatecodeID', 'payment_type']\nnum_cols = [c for c in X_train.columns if c not in cat_cols]\n\nprint(f\"Categorical features ({len(cat_cols)}): {cat_cols}\")\nprint(f\"Numerical features ({len(num_cols)}): {num_cols}\")\n\npreprocessor = ColumnTransformer([\n    ('cat', OrdinalEncoder(handle_unknown='use_encoded_value', unknown_value=-1), cat_cols)\n], remainder='passthrough')   # OrdinalEncoder is faster than OHE for tree models","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:09:19.610070Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:09:19.610304Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:09:19.615206Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:09:19.610265Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:09:19.614271Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Categorical features (6): ['PULocationID', 'DOLocationID', 'PU_Borough', 'DO_Borough', 'RatecodeID', 'payment_type']\nNumerical features (26): ['passenger_count', 'trip_distance', 'hour', 'day_of_week', 'day', 'is_weekend', 'hour_sin', 'hour_cos', 'dow_sin', 'dow_cos', 'is_rush_hour', 'is_night', 'is_holiday', 'trip_duration_min', 'avg_speed_mph', 'is_airport_trip', 'humidity', 'precip', 'snow', 'cloudcover', 'temp_avg', 'rain_flag', 'snow_flag', 'zone_hour_avg_fare', 'zone_hour_ride_count', 'zone_hour_fare_std']\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":7},{"id":"0ffaa376-5fc0-4332-bda8-9aa9329710f2","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 8. Regression: XGBoost Regressor\n\nWe train an XGBoost gradient boosting model to predict `total_amount` directly. The model is configured with:\n\n- **400 estimators** with a low **learning rate of 0.05** to learn gradually and reduce overfitting\n- **Subsampling** (`subsample=0.8`, `colsample_bytree=0.8`) to introduce randomness and improve generalization\n- **L1 and L2 regularization** (`reg_alpha`, `reg_lambda`) to penalize complexity\n- **Early stopping** with a patience of 20 rounds — training halts automatically when validation RMSE stops improving, avoiding manual tuning of `n_estimators`\n\nThe model is evaluated on the held-out test set using three complementary metrics:\n- **MAE** (Mean Absolute Error) — average dollar error, interpretable in fare units\n- **RMSE** (Root Mean Squared Error) — penalizes large errors more heavily\n- **R²** — proportion of fare variance explained by the model\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"7348113d-50e6-4ff9-9ec5-e98a4d4f729b","cell_type":"code","source":"xgb_reg = Pipeline([\n    ('pre', preprocessor),\n    ('reg', XGBRegressor(\n        n_estimators=400,\n        max_depth=7,\n        learning_rate=0.05,\n        subsample=0.8,\n        colsample_bytree=0.8,\n        min_child_weight=5,\n        reg_alpha=0.1,\n        reg_lambda=1.0,\n        n_jobs=-1,\n        random_state=RANDOM_STATE,\n        verbosity=0,\n        early_stopping_rounds=20,\n        eval_metric='rmse'\n    ))\n])\n\n# Prepare eval set with preprocessed data\npre_fit = preprocessor.fit(X_train)\nX_train_enc = pre_fit.transform(X_train)\nX_test_enc  = pre_fit.transform(X_test)\n\nxgb_reg_model = XGBRegressor(\n    n_estimators=400,\n    max_depth=7,\n    learning_rate=0.05,\n    subsample=0.8,\n    colsample_bytree=0.8,\n    min_child_weight=5,\n    reg_alpha=0.1,\n    reg_lambda=1.0,\n    n_jobs=-1,\n    random_state=RANDOM_STATE,\n    verbosity=0,\n    early_stopping_rounds=20,\n    eval_metric='rmse'\n)\n\nxgb_reg_model.fit(\n    X_train_enc, y_train,\n    eval_set=[(X_test_enc, y_test)],\n    verbose=False\n)\n\ny_pred_reg = xgb_reg_model.predict(X_test_enc)\n\nmae  = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_reg)\nrmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_reg))\nr2   = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_reg)\n\nprint(f\"── Regression Results ──────────────\")\nprint(f\"MAE  : ${mae:.2f}\")\nprint(f\"RMSE : ${rmse:.2f}\")\nprint(f\"R²   : {r2:.4f}\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:09:19.616127Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:09:19.616589Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:10:24.757365Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:09:19.616561Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:10:24.756691Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"── Regression Results ──────────────\nMAE  : $1.90\nRMSE : $3.75\nR²   : 0.9541\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":8},{"id":"7dee897c-dfe1-46fb-8ed7-8225bd50259f","cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 8.1 Residual Analysis\n\nWe visualize three diagnostic plots to assess regression model quality:\n\n1. **Predicted vs Actual** — points should cluster tightly around the diagonal. Systematic curves indicate the model is missing non-linear structure.\n2. **Residuals vs Predicted** — ideally centered around zero with constant spread. A fan shape suggests heteroscedasticity (variance increasing with fare size).\n3. **Residual Distribution** — should be approximately symmetric and centered at zero. Heavy tails indicate the model struggles with extreme fares.\n\nTo avoid rendering millions of scatter points (which would hang the kernel), we sample 10,000 points randomly for the first two plots.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"9427c65d-6fef-4407-be6a-565738f82ccc","cell_type":"code","source":"residuals = y_test.values - y_pred_reg\n\n# Sample for plotting — no need to render millions of points\nplot_idx = np.random.choice(len(y_test), size=min(10_000, len(y_test)), replace=False)\ny_test_plot  = y_test.values[plot_idx]\ny_pred_plot  = y_pred_reg[plot_idx]\nresid_plot   = residuals[plot_idx]\n\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18, 5))\n\n# Predicted vs Actual\naxes[0].scatter(y_test_plot, y_pred_plot, alpha=0.3, s=5)\nlims = [min(y_test.min(), y_pred_reg.min()), max(y_test.max(), y_pred_reg.max())]\naxes[0].plot(lims, lims, 'r--', lw=2, label='Perfect prediction')\naxes[0].set_xlabel('Actual Fare ($)')\naxes[0].set_ylabel('Predicted Fare ($)')\naxes[0].set_title('Predicted vs Actual')\naxes[0].legend(loc='upper left')   # ← fixed location, no scanning\n\n# Residuals vs Predicted\naxes[1].scatter(y_pred_plot, resid_plot, alpha=0.3, s=5)\naxes[1].axhline(0, color='r', linestyle='--')\naxes[1].set_xlabel('Predicted Fare ($)')\naxes[1].set_ylabel('Residual ($)')\naxes[1].set_title('Residuals vs Predicted')\n\n# Residual distribution\naxes[2].hist(residuals, bins=80, edgecolor='none')\naxes[2].axvline(0, color='r', linestyle='--')\naxes[2].set_xlabel('Residual ($)')\naxes[2].set_title('Residual Distribution')\n\nplt.suptitle(f'Regression Diagnostics  |  R²={r2:.3f}  MAE=${mae:.2f}  RMSE=${rmse:.2f}', fontsize=13)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:10:24.758237Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:10:24.758490Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:10:25.447071Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:10:24.758467Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:10:25.446367Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1800x500 with 3 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":9},{"id":"28e5765f-a2bb-4405-88c9-6feac4e708ec","cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 8.2 SHAP Feature Importance\n\nSHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) assigns each feature a contribution to each individual prediction, grounded in game theory. Unlike built-in tree importance scores (which measure split frequency or gain), SHAP values are:\n\n- **Consistent** — a feature that matters more always gets a higher SHAP value\n- **Local** — computed per prediction, not just globally\n- **Directional** — the summary plot shows whether high feature values push predictions up or down\n\nWe sample 2,000 test-set rows for speed and display the top 20 most influential features.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"9c21666a-0d72-4606-846f-6a5fbbbbcdfb","cell_type":"code","source":"explainer   = shap.TreeExplainer(xgb_reg_model)\nsample_idx  = np.random.choice(len(X_test_enc), size=2000, replace=False)\nshap_values = explainer.shap_values(X_test_enc[sample_idx])\n\nfeature_names = (\n    cat_cols +\n    [c for c in X_train.columns if c not in cat_cols]\n)\n\nshap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_test_enc[sample_idx], feature_names=feature_names, max_display=20)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:10:25.447795Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:10:25.447976Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:10:34.330034Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:10:25.447956Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:10:34.329214Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 800x950 with 2 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":10},{"id":"63f06b53-ef0d-41f5-bd47-2a7c4fb81d1e","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 9. Classification: Fare Range Prediction\n\nAs a complementary approach, we reframe fare prediction as a **three-class classification problem**. Rather than estimating the exact dollar amount, we predict which fare range a trip falls into.\n\n**Why classification?**\n- It is more robust to fare outliers that are difficult to regress precisely\n- Fare buckets are actionable for operational decisions (e.g., driver incentives, demand balancing)\n- It is easier to evaluate and explain to non-technical stakeholders\n\n**Defining the fare classes:**\nInstead of using fixed dollar thresholds (which would be arbitrary and potentially imbalanced), we use the **33rd and 66th percentile of training fares** to define equal-frequency bins:\n- `low` (class 0): below the 33rd percentile\n- `medium` (class 1): between the 33rd and 66th percentile\n- `high` (class 2): above the 66th percentile\n\nThis guarantees roughly balanced class sizes and makes the thresholds adaptive to the data distribution. Thresholds are derived from training labels only, consistent with our leakage-prevention strategy.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"75c6e098-a15e-457d-b425-6db899beea2c","cell_type":"code","source":"# Compute quantile thresholds on TRAINING labels only\nq33 = y_train.quantile(0.33)\nq66 = y_train.quantile(0.66)\nprint(f\"Fare thresholds → low < ${q33:.2f} ≤ medium < ${q66:.2f} ≤ high\")\n\ndef fare_bucket(fare, q33=q33, q66=q66):\n    if fare < q33:  return 0  # low\n    if fare < q66:  return 1  # medium\n    return 2                  # high\n\ny_train_cls = y_train.apply(fare_bucket)\ny_test_cls  = y_test.apply(fare_bucket)\n\nprint(\"Training class distribution:\")\nprint(y_train_cls.value_counts().rename({0:'low', 1:'medium', 2:'high'}))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:10:34.331388Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:10:34.331657Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:10:35.366247Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:10:34.331633Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:10:35.365182Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Fare thresholds → low < $16.94 ≤ medium < $24.10 ≤ high\nTraining class distribution:\ntotal_amount\nhigh      888647\nlow       861983\nmedium    861748\nName: count, dtype: int64\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":11},{"id":"668e4000-18a7-4072-a03b-0c34e408fbef","cell_type":"code","source":"xgb_clf = XGBClassifier(\n    n_estimators=400,\n    max_depth=7,\n    learning_rate=0.05,\n    subsample=0.8,\n    colsample_bytree=0.8,\n    min_child_weight=5,\n    reg_alpha=0.1,\n    reg_lambda=1.0,\n    use_label_encoder=False,\n    eval_metric='mlogloss',\n    n_jobs=-1,\n    random_state=RANDOM_STATE,\n    verbosity=0,\n    early_stopping_rounds=20\n)\n\nxgb_clf.fit(\n    X_train_enc, y_train_cls,\n    eval_set=[(X_test_enc, y_test_cls)],\n    verbose=False\n)\n\ny_pred_cls = xgb_clf.predict(X_test_enc)\nlabel_map  = {0: 'low', 1: 'medium', 2: 'high'}\n\nprint(\"Classification Report:\")\nprint(classification_report(\n    y_test_cls.map(label_map),\n    pd.Series(y_pred_cls).map(label_map)\n))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:10:35.367616Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:10:35.367873Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:14:14.510901Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:10:35.367853Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:14:14.510264Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Classification Report:\n              precision    recall  f1-score   support\n\n        high       0.92      0.94      0.93    221963\n         low       0.92      0.88      0.90    215123\n      medium       0.84      0.86      0.85    216009\n\n    accuracy                           0.89    653095\n   macro avg       0.89      0.89      0.89    653095\nweighted avg       0.89      0.89      0.89    653095\n\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":12},{"id":"3e092db3-4a1f-46f2-b7b2-e978b6068490","cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 9.1 Confusion Matrix\n\nThe confusion matrix shows how well the model distinguishes between the three fare classes. We pay particular attention to **off-diagonal cells**: misclassifying a *low* fare as *high* (or vice versa) is a more serious error than confusing adjacent classes like *low* and *medium*.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"a58e64e9-9ada-4d23-adde-cfb21983728b","cell_type":"code","source":"cm = confusion_matrix(y_test_cls, y_pred_cls)\ndisp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm, display_labels=['low', 'medium', 'high'])\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 5))\ndisp.plot(ax=ax, colorbar=False, cmap='Blues')\nplt.title('Confusion Matrix – Fare Range Classification')\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:14:14.511723Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:14:14.511895Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:14:14.608904Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:14:14.511878Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:14:14.608257Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 700x500 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":13},{"id":"293e3e5f-3bc5-4e95-ab12-7c818a75eb79","cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 9.2 SHAP Feature Importance (Classifier)\n\nFor the multi-class classifier, SHAP returns one set of values per class. We average the absolute SHAP values across all three classes to obtain a single global importance score per feature, reflecting how much each feature contributes to the classification decision regardless of direction.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"b7ac5d36-2f2b-4d94-9bf8-91dd057e74b1","cell_type":"code","source":"explainer_clf   = shap.TreeExplainer(xgb_clf)\nshap_values_clf = explainer_clf.shap_values(X_test_enc[sample_idx])\n\n# For multi-class, shap_values is a list; use mean absolute across classes\nif isinstance(shap_values_clf, list):\n    mean_shap = np.mean([np.abs(sv) for sv in shap_values_clf], axis=0)\nelse:\n    mean_shap = np.abs(shap_values_clf)\n\nshap.summary_plot(mean_shap, X_test_enc[sample_idx], feature_names=feature_names, max_display=20)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:14:14.609707Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:14:14.609928Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:14:39.028664Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:14:14.609910Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:14:39.027941Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 3100x1700 with 3 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":14},{"id":"9ff621ad-ba6b-4f4e-89d9-a9ab3ab7d3a1","cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 10. Model Comparison & Summary\n\nWe consolidate the evaluation metrics for both models and review the complete modeling pipeline.\n\n**Regression** gives a precise fare estimate — useful for billing forecasts, driver earnings projections, or dynamic pricing systems where an exact dollar value is needed.\n\n**Classification** gives a fare range — useful for operational decisions where a category is sufficient, such as routing, pricing tiers, or passenger-facing fare estimates displayed before booking.\n\nBoth models are trained on the same feature set, use the same train/test split, and share the same leakage-free demand feature pipeline, making their results directly comparable.\n","metadata":{}},{"id":"d5993df2-232a-4c89-8640-0040a39004ca","cell_type":"code","source":"summary = pd.DataFrame([\n    {'Model': 'XGBoost Regressor',  'Metric': 'R²',   'Value': f'{r2:.4f}'},\n    {'Model': 'XGBoost Regressor',  'Metric': 'MAE',  'Value': f'${mae:.2f}'},\n    {'Model': 'XGBoost Regressor',  'Metric': 'RMSE', 'Value': f'${rmse:.2f}'},\n])\n\nfrom sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score\nacc = accuracy_score(y_test_cls, y_pred_cls)\nsummary = pd.concat([summary, pd.DataFrame([\n    {'Model': 'XGBoost Classifier (improved', 'Metric': 'Accuracy', 'Value': f'{acc:.4f}'}\n])], ignore_index=True)\n\nprint(summary.to_string(index=False))\n\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:14:39.029382Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:14:39.029562Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:14:39.042125Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10:14:39.029544Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-19T10:14:39.041485Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"                       Model   Metric  Value\n           XGBoost Regressor       R² 0.9541\n           XGBoost Regressor      MAE  $1.90\n           XGBoost Regressor     RMSE  $3.75\nXGBoost Classifier (improved Accuracy 0.8911\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":15},{"id":"ec1af059-0c26-4f64-8a09-3c3a96f5fb97","cell_type":"code","source":"import json, os\nimport joblib\n\nos.makedirs(\"model_artifacts\", exist_ok=True)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-19T10:14:39.042891Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-19T10:14:39.043111Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-19T10:14:39.051240Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-19T10: